  </div>
  <p class="punch-caption" style="color:rgba(241,233,216,0.5)">A · D · A — rendered as an 1830s punch card would have read it</p>
</header>

<section class="bio">
  <div class="bio-inner">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Biography</p>
      <h2>A Mind Built for Poetical Science</h2>
    </div>

    <p>Augusta Ada Byron was the only legitimate child of the poet Lord Byron, though she never knew her father — her mother, Annabella Milbanke, separated from him within weeks of Ada's birth and steered her daughter's education firmly toward mathematics and logic, hoping to guard her against what she saw as her father's dangerous imagination. It didn't quite work. Ada grew into a thinker who refused to separate the two, later describing her own approach as "poetical science," a phrase that captures exactly what made her singular: a rigorous mathematical mind that never stopped asking what a discipline of numbers might imagine into being.</p>

    <p>In 1833, at seventeen, she met the mathematician Charles Babbage and saw a working model of his Difference Engine, a mechanical calculator of extraordinary ambition for its time. The encounter set the course of her life. Babbage was already sketching plans for a far more advanced machine, the Analytical Engine, capable of being programmed with punched cards borrowed from the Jacquard loom to weave patterns not in cloth, but in numbers. Ada understood immediately that this was not merely a faster adding machine — it was something closer to a general-purpose thinking tool, decades before anyone had the vocabulary to describe it that way.</p>

    <hr class="bio-rule">

    <p>That understanding crystallized in 1843, when Ada translated an Italian engineer's memoir on the Analytical Engine and, at Babbage's suggestion, appended her own notes. Her notes ran roughly three times longer than the original text. Tucked among them, labeled simply "Note G," was a detailed method for the Engine to compute a sequence of Bernoulli numbers — a set of step-by-step instructions widely regarded today as the first algorithm ever published for execution on a machine. She went further still, proposing that such an engine could one day manipulate not just numbers but any symbols governed by rules, even composing music, if the underlying relationships could be expressed formally. It was a leap of imagination the era had no name for.</p>

    <p>Ada Lovelace died in 1852 at only thirty-six, and the Analytical Engine itself was never built in her lifetime — Babbage's ambitions outran the precision manufacturing of the age. For over a century her contribution was known mainly to specialists. It took the rise of the digital computer, more than a hundred years later, for the world to recognize what she had actually written in those margins. In 1980 the U.S. Department of Defense named a programming language, Ada, in her honor, and today the second Tuesday of October is celebrated worldwide as Ada Lovelace Day, honoring women in science and technology.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="notes">
  <div class="notes-inner">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Key Achievements</p>
      <h2>The Notes</h2>
    </div>
    <ol class="note-list">
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;01</span>
        <span class="note-year">1815</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Born in London</h3>
          <p>Daughter of Lord Byron and Annabella Milbanke, raised on a strict diet of mathematics and logic.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;02</span>
        <span class="note-year">1833</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Meets Charles Babbage</h3>
          <p>Sees a demonstration of the Difference Engine at seventeen and begins a lifelong intellectual partnership.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;03</span>
        <span class="note-year">1840</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Studies the Analytical Engine</h3>
          <p>Follows Babbage's Turin lectures on his unbuilt general-purpose machine through Luigi Menabrea's published memoir.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;04</span>
        <span class="note-year">1843</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Publishes her translation and notes</h3>
          <p>Her annotations, nearly three times the length of the original memoir, become her defining work.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;05</span>
        <span class="note-year">1843</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Writes "Note G"</h3>
          <p>A step-by-step method for computing Bernoulli numbers — widely considered the first published algorithm for a machine.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;06</span>
        <span class="note-year">1843</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Envisions computing beyond arithmetic</h3>
          <p>Proposes the Engine could manipulate any rule-governed symbols — including, hypothetically, musical composition.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="note-item">
        <span class="note-tag">Note&nbsp;07</span>
        <span class="note-year">1980</span>
        <div class="note-body">
          <h3>Honored with a language, and a day</h3>
          <p>The U.S. Department of Defense names the Ada programming language after her; Ada Lovelace Day follows in 2009.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="quote-band">
  <span class="quote-mark" aria-hidden="true">&#8220;</span>
  <blockquote>That brain of mine is something more than merely mortal; as time will show.</blockquote>
  <p class="quote-attr">— Ada Lovelace, in a letter to her mother</p>
</section>

